 Bangkok) \u2022 346 policy advisory or technical backstopping services were rendered to Asia-Pacific COs of which 226 were missions to COs.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "cdde6bbd-d731-4f22-b1c3-82e71bdaae09": {"__data__": {"id_": "cdde6bbd-d731-4f22-b1c3-82e71bdaae09", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "48696eaf24ee34bfb0c06f5a9f1e7692d2b227156da1a796b6d3ebc689a8e6e8"}, "2": {"node_id": "5a3e7842-7339-4f15-b59b-578feb0e6c72", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9a39cfa7cfb532af691092f64ab1ffe0febddba56b1da29be05f219707d15fa6"}}, "hash": "ad1d402d751dd3bd54b639156d42eae19721f3e508f2bdab9608309f45554eb1", "text": "\u2022 First Regional Centre Advisory Panel meeting (Democratic Governance) was concluded, bringing together nine eminent members from Asia and the Pacific \u2022 Partnerships support, including project funding MOU, with Rolls Royce, Soka Gakkai, Coca Cola, Mitsui-Sumitomo Insurance and Itochu \u2022 92 learning events organised for 735 CO and RCB participants \u2022 26 ICT for Development events organised, comprising 1,800 participants from governments, CSOs and media \u2022 203 recommendations of experts provided in response to requests of COs and UN partners \u2022 89 knowledge products were produced (reports, primers, toolkits and multimedia) \u2022 RCB staff complement increased from 51 in January to 108 by end 2005 (66% of staff provide targeted support to COs; 34% provide operational services to 19 UN agencies, UNDP Thailand and RCB) \u2022 New office premises inaugurated in May 2005 \u2022 $5.5 million of resources mobilised regionally for tsunami response (Flash appeal: $5.0 million, IDRC: $0.5 million) 3 Introduction The Regional Centre in Bangkok\u2019s (RCB) Annual Report 2005 highlights the RCB team\u2019s major advisory and knowledge services as well as other activities in support of Country Offices (COs) in the Asia-Pacific region from January to December 2005. This report is divided into sections by practice: governance, energy and environment, crisis prevention and recovery, (tsunami, avian influenza and the South Asia earthquake response), and management, and by focus areas: ICT4D and South-South Cooperation, communications and knowledge services (expert referrals, knowledge products and events). Regional programme financial status and staff build-up are also covered. The Asia-Pacific Region in 2005: An Overview 2005 was a year that witnessed Asia's valiant efforts to rise above the tsunami waves set off by the earthquake off the Sumatra coast on 26 December 2004, and scale Himalayan heights to bring succour to the victims of another major earthquake that struck Pakistan and Kashmir on 8 October 2005. The tsunami of 26 December 2004 was a natural disaster of unprecedented scale, in terms of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d111fa30-a8a3-4ce7-b469-0575bb5748a0": {"__data__": {"id_": "d111fa30-a8a3-4ce7-b469-0575bb5748a0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fb84961560cc1915bd7945024abf8a9a49722fb5dc8aa18d468f6f3a0df4ca2a"}}, "hash": "fb84961560cc1915bd7945024abf8a9a49722fb5dc8aa18d468f6f3a0df4ca2a", "text": "the number of lives that it took, and the millions left homeless from Aceh in Indonesia to Andhra Pradesh in India. Aceh and North Sumatra lost the greatest number of lives. The tsunami took lives that could have been saved, if only the region had recognised sooner the real extent of its connectedness, and had taken steps to put in place warning systems for natural disasters. The Special ASEAN Leaders\u2019 Meeting held in Jakarta on 6 January 2005 recognised that the devastation would need an unprecedented global response to assist national governments\u2019 efforts in emergency relief, rehabilitation and reconstruction that could take five to ten years, and agreed to establish a warning system for the region. The World Conference on Disaster Reduction, held in Kobe, Japan, in January 2005, adopted the Hyogo Framework for Action 2005-2015, calling on all countries to integrate disaster risk into political agendas and national policies. The tsunami catastrophe exposed critical weaknesses in governance in the affected countries, forcing some to address long-lasting internal conflicts with greater urgency, but also with a renewed sense of reality. In Indonesia, the Government has reached a tentative peace accord at Helsinki with the separatist Free Aceh Movement (GAM) to end 30 years of fighting. In Sri Lanka, the Government agreed to a joint tsunami relief-monitoring mission with the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), despite strong opposition from within its ranks and continuing uncertainty over prospects for constitutional resolution of the conflict. In Thailand, the Government has shown more sensitivity to the human rights of tsunami victims, including migrants who had earlier been slated for deportation. The Maldives is among the worst affected with per capita reconstruction costs estimated to be higher than in other countries. The tsunami response in the Maldives (and in the other countries) should result in a more efficient and transparent public procurement system. In India, Hindus, Muslims and Christians helped one another as never before to overcome entrenched forms of discrimination based on religion, gender and caste. The importance of governance of the kind that is responsive, accountable, participative and transparent, to secure the well being of people, during disasters and in normal times, has come to the forefront. There have been other upheavals in national governance. The Maldives People\u2019s Assembly is considering constitutional reforms to strengthen fundamental rights, entrench multiparty democracy, separation of powers, effective parliamentary governance, judicial independence, and human rights. Mongolia has blazed a trail by formally adopting the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs), and an additional goal on the Millennium Declaration\u2019s commitment to democracy, good governance and human rights. Bhutan has initiated a 4 process of securing public consent and legitimacy to a new constitution to replace absolute monarchy with a constitutional monarchy, human rights guarantees, democratic elections, and a two-party political system, enabling an effective opposition to the party in power. The presidential election in Iran passed off peacefully, but discussions over the nuclear programme continues to keep Iran in the news. There have been some setbacks during the report period. In Thailand, a different kind of crisis is festering, as the government takes a hard-line approach to Muslim rebellion in the far South. The National Reconciliation Commission (NRC) has warned the Government against excessive use of emergency powers. In Nepal, a coup on 1 February 2005, in which the King took over absolute power, has demonstrated the vulnerability of democracy to crises of legitimacy, brought about most often by inequity and discriminatory treatment of population groups and regions. The Philippines witnessed another upsurge of \u201cpeople\u2019s power\u201d against the President following allegations of electoral malpractices. The importance of constitutionally established means for bringing about changes in political leadership has come to the fore. Apart from political and natural disaster shocks of the kind mentioned above, the region remains vulnerable to economic and humanitarian shocks. Memories of the Asian financial crisis, and before that, the \u201coil shocks\u201d, have not faded. In 2005, rising oil prices continue to be a major threat to economic development. HIV/AIDS is a threat to the prosperity of India and China. Avian influenza threatens to explode into a pandemic in Southeast Asia, from which the numbers of victims could dwarf those of the tsunami. However, the rising awareness of its seriousness among Asia-Pacific decision-makers and senior officials, in both national governments and international bodies, has triggered unprecedented regional cooperation in making large-scale preparations. The UN General Assembly recently endorsed a declaration made by Small Island Developing States (SIDS) requesting expanded trade opportunities, assistance in coping with sea-level rise, and other adverse consequences of climate change, and for renewable energy and cleaner fossil fuel technologies. The", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "070d36d5-bda2-4b11-ab9c-71ec72c238aa": {"__data__": {"id_": "070d36d5-bda2-4b11-ab9c-71ec72c238aa", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6bbd04d9a68aaa069542d7bb34f6e0a9afdc26e37061aa59c5c80e583ba79cee"}}, "hash": "6bbd04d9a68aaa069542d7bb34f6e0a9afdc26e37061aa59c5c80e583ba79cee", "text": "WTO declaration adopted in Hong Kong on 18 December 2005 contains agreements by the developed and large developing countries such as Brazil, China and India to allow duty-free, quota-free access to exports from the least developed countries (LDCs). But importing countries are allowed to set exceptions, applied to crucial products such as textiles, sugar and rice. With unfinished business from Hong Kong, and a U.N. General Assembly five-year review of the Brussels action plan in September 2006, much remains to be done to benefit the LDCs most in need of economic justice and international support. Globalisation has highlighted the importance of regional cooperation. Cooperative mechanisms, such as ASEAN and SAARC, continue to retain sensitivity about principles of sovereignty and non-intervention in the domestic affairs of other states. Conventional approaches to South-South cooperation should give way to innovations. \u201cIn an increasingly interconnected world, progress in the areas of development, security and human rights must go hand in hand\u201d (In Larger Freedom, Kofi Annan, 2005). The potential of ASEAN for moving Myanmar towards democracy, respect for human rights, and good governance, is a case in point. Governance in Asia-Pacific has become an important \u2018global public good\u2019. Uneven development, corruption and consequent lack of legitimacy of the state, are the most serious among the dangers faced by many countries in the region. These factors, more than any others, tend to produce the phenomenon of \u201cfragile states\u201d. Asian countries are addressing these problems, and realise that the achievement of the MDGs, uniformly across population groups and regions is critical. Throughout the region, there is a strong link between poverty, gender inequity and the poor survival rates and wellbeing of the region\u2019s children and women. 5 The importance of multi-sectoral success for the achievement of the MDGs and the critical need for democracy, development, fulfilment of human rights and good governance, emphasised in the Millennium Declaration and at the Millennium Summit, and reiterated in In Larger Freedom, are evident all over Asia. 6 Democratic Governance Strategic Objectives in 20051 1. Increased effectiveness of representative bodies at central and sub-national levels to perform their democratic functions and enhance national poverty reduction goals 2. Poor and disadvantaged groups including indigenous peoples, empowered to seek remedies for injustices and justice institutions enabled to be responsive to claims, consistent with international human rights norms Public administration reform for efficient, effective, responsive and pro-poor public services promoted at central and local levels Increased effectiveness of representative bodies at central and sub-national levels to perform their democratic functions and enhance national poverty reduction goals Representative systems at local and sub-national levels were given a special focus in 2005 both at a programming and policy advisory level. A regional retreat on Representation in Decentralised Governance and Local Service Delivery was held in June 2005, with case studies to be prepared as a result of participant feedback on improving and widening representation at local levels and in turn improving accountability. Leveraging the consolidated regional practice on representation in decentralised governance, the RCB has provided advice to a number of countries. The Government of the Maldives has decided to create local governance authorities with local councils established and empowered drawing on the advice provided by an RCB-led team. The RCB Governance team under this objective also focused on the role of parliamentarians in conflict and post-conflict situations, with case studies from nine COs considered completed and disseminated. These findings will be fed into a donor meeting in Brussels in early 2006. The RCB sponsored the participation of members of electoral commissions from seven Asian countries to attend a meeting of the Asian Association of Electoral Commissions (AAEA) held in Taipei. Policy advisory services in the area of local governance have been provided through missions to Nepal, Cambodia, Sri Lanka, Thailand, Iran and the Maldives. In Sri Lanka, Maldives and Thailand, the local governance dimension of tsunami recovery received special attention. Advocacy work has been undertaken to promote the ratification of the UN Convention against Corruption. The RCB sponsored parliamentarians from ASEAN to Manila for the first meeting of Southeast Asian Parliamentarians against Corruption (SEAPAC). It resulted in a Constitution for SEAPAC, and the Manila Declaration against Corruption and Action Plan for Follow Up. Another area being pursued is on Parliamentary Knowledge Services. The Canadian Parliamentary Centre is undertaking a study on comparative experiences of parliamentary knowledge services for the Asian region. The study will be completed in early 2006 and is expected to assist COs in further developing this hitherto under-emphasised area of parliamentary development. Research on violence in elections and on electoral dispute mechanisms is underway in close cooperation with the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "342e049a-df9f-46a3-a23f-5695533c3927": {"__data__": {"id_": "342e049a-df9f-46a3-a23f-5695533c3927", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "517974bcca84c01102b499771b9f623b98a2d26390a6a1f3f07130a604052aa8"}, "3": {"node_id": "62e501bf-c36d-4e9f-bd9d-ceb5cf674828", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a12a00f4944201f5ac6de2b17abed5ec46ea5921636418e73959ddc191a95cd7"}}, "hash": "2bfa6eb1ae5d236c667e69768b851d733f9a8ebc2ff885c173897e317654d378", "text": "Bureau for Development Policy and policy institutes in the region. The RCB is also focussing on Youth and Young Leaders. Responding to the identified need to look at the linkages between youth, governance and the achievement of the MDGs (a priority reaffirmed by the DG Advisory Panel), RCB, assisted by UNDP Philippines, held an initial 1 As described in the RCB work plan approved by the Management Board on 2 May 2005. 7 Planning Meeting on Developing a Plan of Action on Youth, Governance and the MDGs for Asia and the Pacific on 12-14 December in Manila. Participants from the region included representatives from five COs in the region, and the Regional Centre in Colombo. Representatives from UNDP Argentina and the Bratislava Regional Centre as well as the Global Youth Action Network and Philippine organizations also participated, enriching the discussion with perspectives from other regions, youth and civil society. The meeting served to identify current needs with regard to youth and governance in the region as well as to identify outputs and activities, and the way forward in this area. The meeting also served as a first step in building a community around this area. A Leadership Training Event encompassing five days was held in Thailand for Young Leaders from 20 countries in the Asia Pacific region, focussing on leadership skills, ethics, governance, human rights and negotiation. A cross-section of leaders from all walks of life (parliamentarians, NGOs, private sector, international organizations, etc.) were invited after nomination by UNDP COs. Follow-up activities on regional and national levels will be supported in 2006. Poor and disadvantaged groups including indigenous peoples, empowered to seek remedies for injustices and justice institutions enabled to be responsive to claims, consistent with international human rights norms The promotion of inclusive governance and rights-based approaches (RBAs) including institutional strengthening particularly for disadvantaged groups was emphasised in 2005 within the area of Access to Justice and Human Rights. A regional initiative was launched to document cases of inclusive governance for disadvantaged groups as a collaborative effort between the Asia Regional Governance Programme (ARGP), Asia Pacific Gender Mainstreaming Programme (APGMP) and the Regional Indigenous Peoples\u2019 Programme (RIPP) together with ten COs in the region. In Maldives, the RCB also supported the first National Human Rights Survey of Maldives, through both policy advice and funding, and the inclusion of RBA in the National Development Plan. Policy advice has been provided to the Maldives\u2019 Ministry of Justice on its justice reform programme. Advice has been provided to Bhutan on its constitution, as well as to India and Cambodia on A2J. The regional publication \u201cProgramming for Justice: Access for All - A Practitioner\u2019s Guide to a Human Rights Based Approach to Access to Justice\u201d has been completed and distributed to COs. Its launch took place together with training on RBAs to Access to Justice (A2J) on 22-24 September 2005 in Phnom Penh. Eighteen COs from Asia-Pacific attended, together with government representatives and resource people from academia and civil society. In cooperation with Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights (OHCHR), a regional consultation on \u201cLessons Learned from RBAs in the Asia Pacific\u201d was held on 19-21 September 2005 with representatives from UN agencies and NGOs in the region. A follow-up phase will be carried out with funding from UNICEF, UNESCO, SIDA, OHCHR and UNDP to pilot RBA activities in several countries in Asia. This inter-agency collaboration on human rights is a unique arrangement that should be replicated elsewhere. In the area of Indigenous Peoples\u2019 Rights and Development, technical assistance was provided to Indonesia with advice to the CO on policy and programming, and briefings with the Ministry of Social Affairs and the National Human Rights Commission, resulting in endorsement of the Programme. A study of national and local government regulations and laws affecting indigenous peoples is underway with involvement of Indigenous People\u2019s Organisations and relevant government counterparts. Similar advice and assistance was provided to the Department of Ethnic Minorities of the Ministry of Rural Development in Cambodia to guide development activities in the highland 8 regions. A mechanism for dialogue\u2014an indigenous peoples\u2019 forum has been created. In Bangladesh, the RCB works in close cooperation with the CO including UNDP Chittagong Hill Tracts Development Facility and the Ministry of Chittagong Hill Tracts Affairs with linkages to indigenous peoples\u2019 organisations.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "62e501bf-c36d-4e9f-bd9d-ceb5cf674828": {"__data__": {"id_": "62e501bf-c36d-4e9f-bd9d-ceb5cf674828", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "517974bcca84c01102b499771b9f623b98a2d26390a6a1f3f07130a604052aa8"}, "2": {"node_id": "342e049a-df9f-46a3-a23f-5695533c39