cial Reform Forum to follow up on the Manila Declaration. In 2006, the ARGP, along with APDIP, anticipates support for a tool-kit on judicial reforms to be produced under the auspices of the newly established forum. RCB, in collaboration with the Institute for Democracy and Electoral Assistance, (IDEA) Stockholm, and the Institute for Constitutional Development (INCOD), responded to demand from many countries in the region for comparative lessons from other regions on constitution- making processes. With ARGP support, an inter-regional workshop on the subject was organised in Pretoria, South Africa on 8-10 December. Indonesia \u2013 Promoting indigenous peoples\u2019 rights and development Indigenous peoples are among the most culturally diverse, yet most impoverished. The challenge is to give voice to indigenous peoples and build more inclusive governance structures. UNDP is piloting a regional programme on indigenous peoples\u2019 rights and development using the human rights based approach and multi- stakeholder dialogue, including with IFIs and UN ECOSOC\u2019s Permanent Forum on Indigenous Issues. It is unique to Asia, and the first of its kind in the UN system. Result \u2013 In Indonesia, RCB policy support catalyzed the Government, the National Commission on Human Rights and indigenous organizations to come together, and a new law accommodating the needs and aspirations of indigenous peoples is being formulated. 9 e-Government and e-Governance In partnership with the China\u2019s State Council Informatization Office (SCITO), UNDP China and Cisco Systems organised the 2nd annual Asia-Pacific Public Services Summit in Beijing to address key critical questions on implementation challenges of e-government applications and the need for public sector reform and good governance. The summit was attended by some 160 participants from 18 Asia-Pacific countries (http://www.apdip.net/news/appss1). APDIP and RCB\u2019s governance team has initiated two regional initiatives on Networking of Asian Parliamentarians and a Judicial Reform Network of 21st Century (JRN21). In addition an initiative on pro-poor public service delivery through e-governance was conceptualized. In cooperation with United Nations Centre for Regional Development, APDIP is implementing a project on Capacity Building of Asia-Pacific e-Government Initiatives with 13 participating countries each contributing two case studies. APDIP also contributed to a number of e- government conferences as keynote speaker and resource people among others the International Symposium on E-government in Seoul (8 November 2005) and COMNET Viet Nam (14-15 December 2005). Public administration reform for efficient, effective, responsive, and pro-poor public services promoted In the Public Administration Reform and Anti-Corruption area, beyond the above-mentioned cross-practice linking of parliamentarians and anti-corruption, support has been provided to, among others, Mongolia, Lao PDR and Sri Lanka\u2014the latter with regard to tsunami recovery. In June 2005, the RCB mounted a comprehensive five-person two-week mission to Mongolia in collaboration with the Oslo Governance Centre.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2fa8844e-fca3-4c61-a532-8a2c2ca70907": {"__data__": {"id_": "2fa8844e-fca3-4c61-a532-8a2c2ca70907", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre