ngolian parliament has now ratified the UN Convention Against Corruption and is currently debating a new anti-corruption law. The sharing of the Mongolian MDG 9 experience within Asia-Pacific has captured the attention of Samoa and Timor-Leste, and has also led to the establishment of a new regional community of practice on \u201cIntegrity in Action\u201d, through which capacity will be built for implementation of the UN Convention Against Corruption. 10 poorest countries in the world, 14 of which are in the Asia-Pacific region. Cross-practice activities in this service line are increasingly being undertaken with the RCB Capacity Development team. Missions of a multi-disciplinary nature, consisting of members from different practice teams within the RCB, were undertaken to Sri Lanka and Timor-Leste. In Timor-Leste, a comprehensive programme to strengthen national capacities for public service management has been developed, and is currently being discussed with the Government and other development partners. The RCB also provided advice on the design of an institutional support project to the Office of the President. The RCB also focuses on analysing policy lessons on local service delivery for attainment of the MDGs. The objective of the exercise is to document and disseminate specific operational and policy lessons, especially in rural areas, both from the supply and demand side, on improving access to those local services necessary for poverty reduction and attainment of the MDGs. The RCB is also engaged in the financing aspects of local service delivery for the MDGs. It has drafted the new global primer on Fiscal Decentralisation and Poverty Reduction, and has moderated a UNDP Global Network discussion on the topic. The regional practice team is defining the UNDP niche and entry points in this area. To this end, a regional workshop was held in December on \u201cFinancing Local Service Delivery for the MDGs: Challenges and Opportunities\u201d in New Delhi at the National Institute of Public Finance and Policy (NIPFP). This was a joint initiative of the RCB and UNCDF, in partnership with the NIPFP. Fifteen countries participated. There were two substantive themes of the presentations and discussions: the financing of service delivery/fiscal decentralization, and institutional issues (e.g. accountability) around decentralization. RCB also presented its proposal for country case studies follow-up to be undertaken during 2006. In this regard, a parallel complementary study is also underway to analyse experiences with participatory monitoring of service delivery. Public-Private Partnerships for Urban Environment (PPPUE) PPPUE\u2019s activities complemented the Governance Team\u2019s efforts in the area of public sector reform promotion for efficient, effective, responsive and pro-poor services at central and local levels. The Programme represented RCB in two regional events, namely the Commonwealth Local Government Forum\u2019s Asia-Pacific Regional Symposium on \u201cBetter local services: Improving local government delivery through innovation and partnerships\u201d and the Fourth Asia-Pacific Urban Forum \u201cMaking MDGs Work for Cities\u201d, where it raised awareness and interest of participants in local level PPP as a practical solution to deliver basic services to the Regional support to local service delivery for MDGs The MDGs can be achieved only with major improvements in public service delivery locally.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7b1685da-f3f8-4d2f-9e7d-112914c740f5": {"__data__": {"id_": "7b1685da-f3f8-4d2f-9e7d-112914c740f5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a31815669740727fd60f169d9590e25bd4e93d524444655dd357e685119fb35e"}, "2": {"node_id": "1bbc3e23-e16f-41f4-8093-026548009986", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5b338983dd5805ed1ecddab8a6e36928ff55665035907b87f293ab4a016865a0"}}, "hash": "c36908dc95353b4336410bb0434e6698a3cc711969c424bc9b0197cca8560635", "text": "However, there is surprisingly little attention to both the constraints and opportunities for promoting the role of local governments in this agenda - especially in rural areas where MDG challenges are the greatest. Rather than undertake a set of academic case studies, the regional strategy in Asia-Pacific has been to descend one level and to promote a set of consultative research & advocacy exercises which engage key policy-makers and local government practitioners and create an embryonic local governance network. Result \u2013 The network has been infused with cross- country exchange and regional advocacy on policy constraints", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "cc1d11f6-0a26-426b-b1a0-db058da30b66": {"__data__": {"id_": "cc1d11f6-0a26-426b-b1a0-db058da30b66", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-