; and an initial review of the existing laws, rules, regulations and policy on urban services was completed; b) the Iran CO in exploring new approaches that entail the participation of the private sector and civil society in the delivery of basic urban services to poor and informal settlements of two selected municipalities. Key outputs are: the PPPUE toolkit \u201cTools for Pro-Poor Municipal PPP\u201d translated and published in Farsi (Persian) and disseminated through the Iran Association of Municipalities; two regional multi- stakeholder workshops. Technical support and guidance was provided to COs in the region in developing their PPPUE projects and to effectively apply for its second wave of Innovative Partnerships Grant (IPG) support. Cambodia, India and the Philippines COs were selected to receive the Grant to test- experiment with PPP arrangements of delivering services to the poor. CO focal points together with their lead implementing partner organisations\u2019 representatives were invited to attend a week-long orientation meeting in Johannesburg, where PPP concept, frameworks and options, its pro-poor and MDG dimensions, and implications for policy, institutional and regulatory changes were examined. The Programme\u2019s efforts were also directed towards an analysis of demand in the region for such support, and areas were identified for intervention. Aid Coordination and Management The RCB\u2019s Aid Coordination team has focused since March 2005 on responding to the pressing needs of tsunami-affected countries to enhance their national aid coordination capacities. UNDP proposed a package of aid coordination support at the High-Level Coordination Meeting on Rehabilitation and Reconstruction of Tsunami-affected Countries hosted in March 2005 by the ADB in Manila. In April 2005, UNDP received requests for support from the Governments of Sri Lanka, Maldives and Thailand. These centred on assisting these Governments in reinforcing their coordination staff and capacity, and customising a tsunami resources and results tracking system to meet their specific needs. By June 2005, customised versions of the Development Assistance Database (DAD) were installed and operational within the Government departments in all three countries and available on-line to the public. In September 2005, the Government of Indonesia requested the RCB to provide similar policy and technical support to its reconstruction authority in Aceh (BRR). The Recovery Aceh/Nias Database (RAN, as the DAD is called there) was publicly launched in Aceh on 28 October 2005. Data on all projects is accessible to all through the Internet, either by accessing the four operational DADs directly or through the Government-run websites, with weekly reports published automatically to the site. \u2022 Indonesia: http://rand.brr.go.id/RAND/ \u2022 Maldives: http://dad.finance.gov.mv/ \u2022 Sri Lanka: http://dad.tafren.gov.lk/dad/ \u2022 Thailand: http://dadthailand.mfa.go.th/dad/ 12 The country-level tsunami work has been brought together within a single window whereby data on resources and results from all four countries can be analysed through maps, charts and reports in the Regional Tsunami DAD based in the RCB (http://tsunamitracking.undp.or.th/dadregional). Information on all four countries as well as pre-defined reports and charts from the national DADs can also be accessed through a regional tsunami web portal (http://tsunamitracking.org), which presents relevant information in a user-friendly, easily accessible manner.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7cc68c7b-4e44-4cea-926e-3ee9128041a4": {"__data__": {"id_": "7cc68c7b-4e44-4cea-926e-3ee9128041a4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nation