ope to make", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "103c6f89-c8c6-4aa9-9274-4279799ff5a0": {"__data__": {"id_": "103c6f89-c8c6-4aa9-9274-4279799ff5a0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8b3be23a305b040badc38233fb3d69cc1093b16399f79945ec5d738f32f77289"}}, "hash": "8b3be23a305b040badc38233fb3d69cc1093b16399f79945ec5d738f32f77289", "text": "progress regarding the: \u2022 harmonisation and alignment agenda consolidated in Paris in March 2005; and, \u2022 integration of aid within a national budget framework reflecting the priorities of national MDG-based Poverty Reduction Strategies. In each country, the RCB and CO collaboration seeks to develop a package of support that is tailored closely to the specific national requirements. The package marries capacity development measures and policy advice with customised aid and budget tracking technology. The Governments of Maldives, India and Vietnam have expressed their interest in fostering the linkage between official development assistance (ODA) and the respective national public investment programme through a more sophisticated public finance management system. In December, the Aid Coordination team organized a Knowledge Sharing Workshop on Lessons Learnt on Tsunami Aid Coordination in Bangkok, which brought together aid coordination advisers and practitioners from different countries. Gender Mainstreaming The Asia Pacific Gender Mainstreaming Programme (APGMP), hosted at the Regional Centre in Colombo (RCC), has been working closely with regional programmes and practice teams based at the Regional Centre in Bangkok. In addition, the two Bangkok-based members of the Gender team have been providing continuous policy support and technical backstopping to COs in the region on documents, policy notes and in developing proposals for funding. In the area of governance, APGMP is currently working with the regional programmes on governance and indigenous peoples on a regional series highlighting inclusive governance which will feature case studies from Afghanistan, Iran and Tonga. These focus on exploring issues on women\u2019s access to resources and basic rights as well as the reasons for their exclusion from the democratic processes. The gender programme in partnership with the Regional Indigenous Peoples\u2019 Programme (RIPP) has initiated a country-exchange between Bangladesh and Malaysia to train indigenous women in decision-making and provide them with the opportunity to learn from each others\u2019 experiences and facilitate a broader comprehension of their rights towards building their capability to protect such rights when violated. The APGMP completed a training workshop on Gender Responsive Budgeting to provide a platform for government representatives, CSOs, researchers and academics from 14 countries in the region to dialogue on work that has 13 already been done in countries in this area and to develop a way forward on gender responsive budgets, and the availability and use of disaggregated data. The APGMP also partnered other regional programmes to carry out a training course for young leaders in governance. There is a special emphasis on young women in order to further capacitate them with leadership skills in their area of work as parliamentarians, journalists, activists, etc. In other practice areas (ICT, Energy and Environment), the Gender team co-hosted a workshop on \u2018Mapping Gender in the Information Society\u2019 with APDIP in Bangkok as a preparatory meeting for the World Summit on the Information Society (WSIS). It brought together activists from the academic and grassroots level to dialogue on the gender perspectives of the WSIS and to articulate the gender concerns that exist in the information society into the WSIS debate. Furthermore, the Gender team provided technical support to the Energy and Environment team to reflect gender perspectives in the energy rapid assessment and gap analysis initiative for the region. The two regional centres also co-hosted a regional gender thematic trust fund project. As part of the project, a synthesis paper on gender mainstreaming in UNDP practice areas was completed through ten country cases from the region. This was subsequently shared at a regional workshop with participation from 14 COs, both regional centres and HQs. Capacity Development in the Governance Programme Area Capacity development has been increasingly positioned as cross-cutting to other practice areas and this is reflected in the integrated work plan of the Regional Centres in Bangkok and Colombo. The tsunami brought to light critical capacity gaps in the area of governance, further detailed below in the Crisis Prevention and Recovery (CPR) section. Significant capacity development inputs have been provided in the areas of legislatures and elections. COs also demanded enhancement of capacities for working on indigenous peoples\u2019 issues including strengthening of the policy framework pertaining to indigenous peoples. Capacity 2015 has looked to pilot innovations and new approaches in development that lend themselves to scaling up and enhancing knowledge. Lessons from on-the-ground initiatives and from policy forums have been captured and codified into programming guidelines, toolkits and other resource materials that help to \u2018operationalise\u2019 capacity development. The focus of capacity development support to the Governance team has been in the area of public sector management (PSM). The Capacity Development team has been supporting the development of three country programmes in Sri Lanka (related to tsunami", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "106f1d23-a8b3-45c8-99de-40903c8a294f": {"__data__": {"id_": "106f1d23-a8b3-45c8-99de-40903c8a294f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "344a2326d320f26971215e9eb3b53e43603e8885dab1f2054506868b62f2391e"}, "3": {"node_id": "817d2f1a-a9fa-4daf-a677-24925caa679c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "832b40c379976f1ec014ec9c601888168abc2825cf888d1d95b1fac06175e021"}}, "hash": "2ee42bf8f35e392398ec3c974cabd7b419ddf317e3aba8827c179cc5787bdc23", "text": "recovery), Timor-Leste and Afghanistan. In each of these cases, support to developing programmes with a thrust on developing national capacity was emphasised. The particular focus of the Capacity Development team has been to provide know-how on capacity assessments that establish baseline capacities in the civil Bangladesh and Malaysia \u2013 Strengthening the role of women in decision-making Women need to be involved in decisions that affect them, their families and communities. Indigenous women face the triple burden of discrimination on the basis of gender, ethnicity and social status. Building on UNDP country office and civil society efforts, a training programme, aimed at developing women\u2019s confidence and capacity to engage in decision-making, has been conducted in indigenous peoples\u2019 areas in Bangladesh (Chittagong Hill Tracts) and Malaysia (Sabah). The training is oriented to informing them of their rights, thereby raising awareness of their position and potential in society. The training is complemented by enabling women from the two areas to exchange experiences. Results \u2013 Women have been enabled to play a meaningful role in decision-making, and have learned from each other\u2019s skills and experiences. 14 service and forward planning. This support comes in the form of providing toolkits and hands on advice to Ministries and/or actors in the civil service. In the area of Local Governance, the team has recently started an initiative with the Galing Pook Foundation in the Philippines to institute an award recognising innovations in capacity development at the local level in support of achieving the MDGs. In the Access to Justice area, the Capacity Development team has delivered sessions on integrating capacity development and rights-based approaches in development. In Cambodia, Capacity 2015 in partnership with the country office has developed a video on the experiences and lessons learned in strengthening capacities of the government\u2019s local fisheries offices and the communities in managing community