ae3e6c1-cf9e-40d6-946c-5866b7fdb752", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7c7b8ecd5f083df3e17d1d866c25296ff87c63881b9d09db27770bd1ad2bf224"}, "3": {"node_id": "d345b8ed-fc53-46f3-89d6-645f2808c004", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "69cd72cd9fb998c412f2b9db489626376faafe7c6afb6e042be8b9e015f2928e"}}, "hash": "ffacde19b7479d05cff77b1bacd9d5af9d847d88e918ea9c265ef00043a37715", "text": "Mugnai, Aparna Basnyat, Roohi Metcalfe 10. Regional HRBA Lessons Learned Workshop Q3 Thailand R. Sudarshan, Chandra Roy, Arusha Stanislaus 3 RCB (co-)organized or (co-)sponsored events are shown in this table. 19 Title Date Location Focal Point 11. Capacity Development for Public Sector Management Q3 Timor- Leste Patrick Keuleers, Niloy Banerjee 12. Local Service Delivery for the MDGs Q4 India Roger Shotton, Henrik Larsen, Santosh Mehrotra 13. Training Workshop on Decision Making for Indigenous Women Q4 Malaysia Chandra Roy, Helen Leake 14. Orientation for UNDP CO Focal Points and their Lead implementing partner \u2018s representatives for PPPUE 2nd generation IPG projects Q4 Johannes- burg Batdelger Luuzan 20 Energy and Environment Strategic Objectives in 2005 1. National policy frameworks that reflect environmental and energy access considerations in poverty reduction and sustainable development strategies established 2. Access to energy services, electricity or cleaner fuels in rural areas increased 3. Governments and local communities empowered to better manage biodiversity and the ecosystem services it provides. National policy frameworks that reflect environmental and energy access considerations in poverty reduction and sustainable development strategies established The environment-poverty linkage was the main focus of the environmental mainstreaming work. A project development workshop was held in Bangkok involving CO focal points and major development partners (ESCAP, UNEP, ADB and IUCN) in March 2005. The Poverty Environment Initiative (PEI) was subsequently launched at the Ministerial Conference on Environment and Development in Seoul in April 2005. PEI meetings were held in Bhutan and Bangladesh to provide a dialogue space for the integration of environmental concerns of the poor into national policy planning and to create a better understanding of how poverty- environment (P-E) activities have been carried out in the region. These meetings were also attended by representatives from Mongolia, Lao PDR, Cambodia, Sri Lanka and Nepal. A preparatory assistance (PA) document was drafted in collaboration with the RCC and COs. The PA contemplates support to a number of studies on poverty \u2013 environment linkages, in relation to UNDP programmes. In addition, the environment-governance linkages were explored with a view to embracing community-based approaches to natural resource management and sustainable development through policy recommendations and practical measures that will emphasise access, control and management of natural resources as well as the role of formal and informal institutions in shaping people\u2019s resource endowments and entitlements. Specific activities included: preparatory work for cross-border community dialogue in the Lower Mekong region; the completion of five environmental governance case studies at the local level in Nepal, Philippines, Samoa, Thailand and Mongolia; a launch of seven environmental governance pilots in Sri Lanka, Maldives, Timor-Leste, China, Pakistan, Indonesia and Cambodia; targeted policy advice to UNDP Indonesia on mainstreaming environmental strategy and tsunami response; and, review of Cambodia National Sustainable Community dialogues across frontiers Communities sometimes suffer in silence. Along both banks of the huge Mekong river, villagers are concerned about the steady erosion of the river which is literally eating into their livelihoods. The RCB\u2019s regional environmental governance programme was launched to empower local communities to take part in the decision making processes that may impact the environment, and to ensure fair access to natural resources. One of its initiatives relies on RCB working with local UN volunteers identified by the country offices of Thailand, Lao PDR, and Cambodia to facilitate community-to- community dialogues among three river-bank communities. Results \u2013 Communities discovered many commonalities through their talks and exchanged ideas. They learned, were empowered, and have developed strategies based on which they are taking their causes to their respective local authorities. 21 Development Plan and Sri Lanka\u2019s MDG Report. National Capacity Self Assessment (NCSA) project development support and implementation assistance, which helps countries to identify their capacity development priorities in order to effectively fulfil their global environmental commitments, were provided to 30 countries in the region As a follow up to the NCSA process, support to the development of GEF funded cross-cutting capacity development projects were provided to five countries \u2013 Philippines, Cambodia, Bhutan, Lao PDR and Vietnam. Support for mainstreaming played a key role in the RCB\u2019s efforts to assist country offices in the region with programming, including the development of a major mainstreaming programme in Afghanistan, and virtual support in Cambodia and Sri Lanka.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d345b8ed-fc53-46f3-89d6-645f2808c004": {"__data__": {"id_": "d345b8ed-fc53-46f3-89d6-645f2808c004", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7c7b8ecd5f083df3e17d1d866c25296ff87c63881b9d09db27770bd1ad2bf224"}, "2": {"node_id": "9ae3e6c1-cf9e-40d6-946c-5866b7fdb752", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ffacde19b7479d05cff77b1bacd9d5af9d847d88e918ea9c265ef00043a37715"}}, "hash": "69cd72cd9fb998c412f2b9db489626376faafe7c6afb6e042be8b9e015f2928e", "text": "Under the Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR), technical assistance was provided in the implementation of an ongoing project on the development of national energy policies and strategic action plans covering 14 Pacific Islands Access to energy services, electricity or cleaner fuels in rural areas increased In the area of energy and climate change, the focus was on poverty reduction and environmental sustainability. The three policy studies", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0a788093-2470-4572-9c3f-9a789e43d508": {"__data__": {"id_": "0a788093-2470-4572-9c3f-9a789e43d508", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "295c3b2a805f3a3ac4f3584001d7cc981416bf853a0e5aca9a007d95627022dd"}}, "hash": "295c3b2a805f3a3ac4f3584001d7cc981416bf853a0e5aca9a007d95627022dd", "text": "launched by the Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) are being conducted by well-known institutes from the Asia Pacific region and expected to be completed by mid-2006. These three policy studies will: 1) analyse the impact of rising oil prices on the poor and the implications for the achievement of the MDGs; 2) analyse cross-border energy trade and its impact on the poor; and 3) undertake a regional mapping of options to promote private investments in alternative energy sources for the poor. In addition the Energy Team contributed to the development of the GEF Programming Toolkit on the Productive Uses of Renewable Energy, which is currently being finalised by UNDP/GEF. Capacity development activities were formulated to support UNDP COs and host countries in the region to respond to multilateral conventions and energy access issues to meet MDGs. Policy advice and technical support were provided to Bangladesh, Cambodia and Pakistan to prepare medium-term country strategy papers on energy and climate change. Joint missions by the energy and environment team were conducted to prepare an E&E country programme framework for Afghanistan and a GEF country strategy framework for Indonesia. Technical support was also provided to Cambodia, Indonesia, Lao PDR, Mongolia, Philippines and Vietnam in the finalisation of country case studies and the design of project concept notes for rural energy services under the Global Village Energy Partnership (a UNDP and World Bank joint initiative). Energy-poverty and climate change workshops were organised collaboratively, benefiting 76 professionals \u2013 CO focal points and national counterparts from Cambodia, Indonesia, Lao PDR, Mongolia, Philippines, Vietnam, India, China, Malaysia, Pakistan, Maldives, Bangladesh, Iran and Thailand. Country-specific trainings were also provided to: 42 professionals in Mongolia on methodologies to identify development objectives supporting clean energy use, energy resource needs and technology assessment at national and sector levels; while 15 professionals in Timor-Leste were trained on methodologies to identify energy needs, resource and technology assessment at the community level including identification of villages for programme implementation. Other country level project development and policy advisory support is outlined in below table. Technical assistance was also provided per the table below to several countries in the performance of their GEF project implementation reviews. Moreover, several UNDP COs were assisted in the preparation of their second national communications proposal on Climate Change in compliance of host country commitments to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCC). 22 The Community of Energy Sub-Practice in Asia-Pacific Region (CEPAP) has been instrumental in promoting the exchange of information and lessons learned in an effective way supporting the work of the REP-PoR, as well as in the development of three UNDP/GEF regional initiatives on: (1) Energy Standards and Labelling (Asia); (2) Energy Systems Optimisation (Asia); and, (3) GHG Abatement through Renewable Energy (the Pacific). The Gap analysis of the REP-PoR identifies country level gaps in institutional, policy, technology, capacity and access to knowledge and information limiting access to energy for the poor and has been completed in 15 Asian countries and 14 Pacific Island countries. The country reports are currently being summarised for publication. A synthesis report is also under preparation, drawing on key gaps that deter access to energy for the poor in the region. The Pacific Rapid Assessment and Gap Analysis report was finalized at the end of December followed by a Gender and Energy Add-on Report. This rapid assessment provides the baselines and a framework for programming of energy services provision for the poor at the country level in the Pacific. The Energy component of the Energy and Environment Thematic Trust Fund (TTF) launched its fourth round funding globally in October 2005. The winners for the funding announced in December include Bhutan, Cambodia, China, Nepal and Timor-Leste. In this regard, technical support was provided for the design of project concept notes, coordination for the funding submission and the formulation of the project documents. The TTF funded projects are expected to start in February 2006. Governments and local communities empowered to better manage biodiversity and the ecosystem services it provides Environmental management of the region\u2019s vast resources and rich biodiversity presents the greatest challenge, particularly when this responsibility needs to give priority to the enhancement of livelihood opportunities and security of people living on the margins of poverty. Capacity development and technical assistance were given to China in the formulation of a national- level agricultural diversity conservation project, and to Bangladesh and Bhutan in the formulation of projects on agro- biodiversity conservation and eco-tourism. Similar assistance was given to India in GEF projects on medicinal plants, markets access, wetlands conservation and conservation of traditional rice varieties. Preparatory assistance was provided", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4fb0e9ed-53f2-4a39-bee2-a7e61eba62bc": {"__data__": {"id_": "4fb0e9ed-53f2-4a39-bee2-a7e61eba62bc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "07c950f4879a53d97cd8aa4326d821cffe071957d0d0af545546a028e8097032"}, "3": {"node_id": "97406a7f-2e7b-4c1c-9941-25d897920268", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programm