ecovery Framework document, as well as a review of all other chapters. Other technical assistance that was provided to COs includes: the preparation of protected area governance case studies for Cambodia and Malaysia and M&E support to Nepal, Philippines, Malaysia, Cambodia, Vietnam, Mongolia and China. In the second half of 2005, significant technical assistance was provided to 17 countries in the region in developing and submitting Project Implementation Reviews of on-going GEF-funded projects. These reviews highlighted the progress and impacts of UNDP\u2019s GEF-funded portfolio of conservation projects, and formed the basis for overall sub-regional project impact reports that summarised UNDP\u2019s contribution to GEF implementation in the region. Both within and outside UNDP, partnerships were forged and strengthened to enhance the impact of on-going and planned programme initiatives. Partnership discussions were held with a diverse array of organisations including sister multilateral agencies (the World Bank, UNEP and IFAD), international NGOs (IUCN, the Nature Conservancy, Wildlife Conservation Society, WWF and Conservation International) and regional institutions (Asian Disaster Preparedness Centre, RECOFTC and ASEAN Secretariat), while within the RCB, cross-practice links were developed with the Regional Indigenous Peoples Programme amongst others. Increasingly, RCB support in the areas of biodiversity and NRM focused on developing more programmatic and strategic portfolios for our clients. In Indonesia, a RCB team developed a GEF Strategy, and in India support was provided to streamlining the GEF biodiversity portfolio. In addition, lessons from UNDP biodiversity projects were distilled for a note on Biodiversity and MDGs, and an assessment of governance issues in protected areas. Capacity Development in the E&E Programme Area The above-mentioned Regional Environmental Governance Programme case studies from five countries reveal strong demand for community capacity to engage and influence policy dialogue/debate around E&E issues. Pilot projects have been initiated to develop the capacity of the state to engage in environmental governance. The trans-boundary community dialogue initiative for the Lower Mekong River Basin Area reveals the primary importance of supporting links across country borders. Support has been provided to Philippines, Cambodia, Bhutan and China to formulate new programmes for capacity development based on the GEF-NCSAs and for GEF funding. Capacity 2015 has provided technical inputs in strengthening local government and community capacities for participating in environmental management and monitoring and addressing poverty concerns through effective natural resources management. Missions: Programme Development/Technical Backstopping/Policy Advice Country Practice / Service Line \u2013 Purpose Dates Specialist(s) 1. Indonesia Development of CO Environment Strategy Based Outcome Evaluation, Advice on 2005 Pipeline and Aceh Tsunami Response; Technical Support of ATSEF National Stakeholder Meeting 16\u201321 January Sergio Feld 2.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "97406a7f-2e7b-4c1c-9941-25d897920268": {"__data__": {"id_": "97406a7f-2e7b-4c1c-9941-25d897920268", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Developmen