cal expertise Strengthen capacities for the development of post-conflict recovery frameworks, reintegration programmes and conflict prevention and peace building Activities to meet this objective have been under the management of BCPR HQ working directly with COs. In the Pacific activities have been implemented through the Pacific Sub- Regional Centre in Suva (PRSC). In collaboration with PSRC, CPR advisers have been supporting the PNG CO to develop a comprehensive Crisis Prevention and Recovery Programme for BCPR funding. Strengthen disaster risk management and recovery capacity at regional, national and local levels Activities in support of the above objective to enhance disaster risk management and recovery capacity have been dominated by the Indian Ocean Tsunami Disaster, the Pakistan/Kashmir earthquake and avian influenza. While the entire UN system, in fact the entire world, has joined together in response to the tsunami disaster and in support of the tsunami affected countries, UNDP has taken a major role in tsunami recovery efforts. All of the RCB practice teams have contributed to these corporate efforts. Immediately following the tsunami disaster, the RCB formed a response team to coordinate the wide range of activities and share information to enhance the RCB support within the broader UNDP and UN System response to the tsunami disaster. The Crisis Prevention and Recovery (CPR) practice has played a major role in providing additional recovery capacity to UNDP COs. In turn, the COs are supporting the development of additional recovery capacity within the national and local governments in the affected countries. The two CPR Regional Disaster Reduction Advisors (RDRAs) for Asia were immediately assigned to two of the affected countries, with one deployed to Sri Lanka and the other supporting Thailand CO. The other affected countries were supported with Advisors sent from headquarters. All of the affected countries had immediate CPR surge capacity added to their operations within days of the event. The Advisors assisted the COs with technical backstopping of TRAC 1.1.3 emergency cash grants, the development of the flash appeal inputs for the COs, and also supported general situation reporting as well as advice on longer- term recovery programming. Most of the Delhi-based RDRA\u2019s work has focused on recovery support to capacity building for risk reduction the Tsunami affected countries (India, Sri Lanka and the Maldives). At the regulatory policy level, worthy of note is CPR support to Sri Lanka CO with the development of a Disaster Management Act, which was passed by the Government in May 2005. This support included policy dialogue and liaison with the relevant government counterparts and support in the drafting of the bill. In the last quarter of 2005 the CPR Adviser provided substantial inputs for a Sri Lanka Government Disaster Reduction Management Road Map as well as drafting support. As important is RDRA\u2019s support to Sri Lanka for the conceptualization and implementation of capacity building initiatives in DRM. 40 In the Maldives, CPR practice team has been providing TA for capacity building initiatives in DRM and support for the implementation of the CO DRM work plan. Moreover, CPR mobilized DRM experts to take forward the DRM agenda in the Maldives and, provided support for the development of disaster information systems and early warning systems and multi-hazard risk assessments. The RCB also conducted comparative research on engaging CSO\u2019s for Sri Lanka and provided short lists of recommended experts based on collated rosters of existing and new experts to assist with recovery planning, programming and implementation, with candidates provided to each country. In addition to the assistance provided directly to the tsunami-affected countries, the CPR team also actively engaged in International Early Warning System Development Workshops; participated in the World Bank-UNDP Joint Assessment Mission in India as well as in the joint OCHA/UNDG/UNDP Recovery Coordination Needs Assessment Mission to Sri Lanka, Maldives and Indonesia; and designed the UNDP Regional Capacity Building Programme for Tsunami Recovery. Launched in October 2005, this Regional Capacity Building Programme will support further regional recovery and risk reduction efforts. The programme\u2019s main objectives are to help increase the capacity of countries affected by the Indian Ocean Tsunami to undertake post- disaster recovery, and to mitigate the risk that would ensue from any future natural disasters. To achieve these goals, the programme will focus on: improving information management systems for disaster and beneficiary tracking; helping improve Early Warning Systems and ensuring that notions of risk reduction are integrated into future recovery and development projects; as well as by offering opportunities for training and learning to national and regional natural disaster experts. Programme Team members", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "325e1d41-3be3-4ac9-a838-d4d2d7fa68c3": {"__data__": {"id_": "325e1d41-3be3-4ac9-a838-d4d2d7fa68c3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4c9b4a2b4253c6399661f3317cb0058a31903b0fdd4efbdc3733c85e99fcf581"}, "3": {"node_id": "58ad49af-d69d-423e-9e7d-f8221a35b177", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "435e0533a777bc9986a986b18ef33ceb24e702839ab0b53258d1ee1b38c95eab"}}, "hash": "1e27f5dcea7a46f453b928c97d6907cbcad91ba26053d8441b69116573fac536", "text": "have conducted several Country Office assessment Missions to affected countries (Sri Lanka, Maldives, India, Indonesia, Thailand). Following these missions, Country Offices have confirmed the relevance and timeliness of implementing the specific component activities. Work plan preparation for 2006 commenced in December 2005 and will be finalised in January 2006 Delhi based CPR RDRA also mobilized funds and provided conceptualization support to the CO for EWS initiatives in Tamil Nadu and provided a vital link between the Tsunami Regional Programme and the UN System Recovery initiatives in the Tsunami affected states. In Pakistan, Delhi-based CPR adviser and Team provided post earthquake coordination and early recovery support to UNDP Pakistan and are currently providing TA for the establishment of a Enhancing Aid Transparency in the Tsunami Countries Days after the Tsunami struck, aid coordination shot to top of agenda for Governments struggling to coordinate hugely increased resources & actors. At the ADB Conference in Manila in March 2005, UNDP offered technical assistance which included people and the Development Assistance Database (DAD) \u2013 proven in Afghanistan. The Response from Governments was an emphatic \u201cyes\u201d. Within 10 days, RCB fielded missions to Sri Lanka, Maldives, Thailand, and Aceh joined in August. Critical partnerships have benefiting from strong personal engagement of UN Special Envoy President Clinton \u2013 who signed 130 letters asking Ministers and NGO heads to back the DAD. Results \u2013RCB established and funded 4 world class systems to track Tsunami resources and results \u2013 each customised to meet national requirements. Mutual accountability of Governments to donors, and donors to governments has been enhanced. There is systematic downward accountability to affected communities (including access to gender disaggregated data). The DAD helps Government, donors, and citizens answer questions like: what are donors doing? Are there any results? Will it benefit me? How do we unblock bottlenecks? 41 comprehensive DRM Programme, aimed at enhancing the capacities of both UNDP as well as national and local level government agencies. In Iran, the CO and the government agreed on a 5-Year DRM Programme, which was officially signed in January 2006. BCPR Delhi provided conceptualization support for the Programme document. Support was provided to Bhutan with the implementation of two PAs \u2013 Urban Earthquake Vulnerability Risk and Integrated Disaster Reduction Management. Both these initiatives were supported financially, technically and to a certain extent operationally by CPR Team in Delhi. This has resulted in shifting UNDP Bhutan/Government policy thinking on the need for a DRM Road Map and a comprehensive DRM Capacity Building Programme. A unique opportunity for disaster risk reduction has engaged the CPR practice since June 2005. The rising awareness of the seriousness of Avian Influenza (AI) and the potential it creates for a catastrophic pandemic influenza to emerge has caused the UNCTs in Southeast Asia to organise sub- regional meetings on the topic. At the request of the RCs in the \u201cfrontline\u201d avian influenza countries, an ad-hoc UN regional interagency team has been established to provide technical support to the national-level avian influenza and pandemic influenza preparedness efforts. The teams are lead technically by WHO on the human health and FAO on the animal health, with UNOCHA providing contingency planning expertise, UNDP providing risk reduction expertise and UNICEF providing Information, Education and Communication (IEC) expertise as well as health sector programmatic expertise. The Bangkok-based Regional Disaster Reduction Advisor has facilitated the coordination of the team\u2019s activities and participated in three joint missions in support of Vietnam, Cambodia and Lao PDR. The effective role played by the CPR adviser in facilitating Inter-Agency Coordination, has led to the establishment of a new BCPR funded position - Regional Inter-Agency Coordinator on Avian and Human Influenza - reporting to the UN System Influenza Coordinator. Selected in December 2005, the AI Coordinator will commence duty in January 2006 and will work out of the regional UNOCHA office. In addition to tsunami, earthquake and avian influenza pandemic preparedness efforts, the CPR Advisors supported broader disaster risk reduction efforts in the region. One of the major non-tsunami areas of activity was regional support for efforts at \u201cmainstreaming\u201d disaster risk reduction into development planning.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "58ad49af-d69d-423e-9e7d-f8221a35b177": {"__data__": {"id_": "58ad49af-d69d-423e-9e7d-f8221a35b177", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-ann