ps": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "283e76e0264a23eef8d95592a8b50ad26a710077ba157c921c76fa9a5743a076"}, "3": {"node_id": "634fd51b-3efa-42c7-8dd3-296db6ed24d8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "df6521a573f57ee912da3bc6939bf312ef5e02ebd31a6af9af7e6b849e32af99"}}, "hash": "91e1a1309fde70de61371dcd22edb608f3671134b129c3405e76f166e971371e", "text": "RCB initiated the formation of a small UN interagency Avian and Human Influenza Preparedness Team. The team\u2019s missions to Vietnam, Cambodia, and Lao PDR have served to support the respective UNCT\u2019s efforts to raise the issue above the animal and human health sectors. Broad inter-ministerial coordination for avian influenza control and for pandemic influenza preparedness also leveraged UNDP\u2019s substantive experience with disaster management and governance. Results \u2013 A better level of pandemic preparedness has been achieved regionally and globally. Governments have produced draft contingency plans, with donor backing. Inter-agency cooperation has improved regionally and at the country level with clear agreement on WHO and FAO in the technical lead; UNICEF providing strong Information/Education/Communications support; and UNDP providing disaster management expertise with OCHA supporting contingency planning efforts. 42 regional offices in Bangkok, and strengthened existing relationships with UNESCAP. Interaction with UNESCAP included attending a national level workshop in Vietnam as part of the CPR supported UNESCAP implemented project on Methodologies for Assessing the Socio- Economic Impacts of Disasters (tailoring the ECLAC methodology to Asia). Engagement with regional institutions has resulted in the production of two significant documents: (1) \u201cGender Dimensions in Disaster Management: A Guide for South Asia\u201d produced in partnership with the Intermediate Technologies Development Group (ITDG); and, (2) a \u201cPrimer on Integrated Flood Risk Management in Asia\u201d produced in partnership with the ADPC. The Advisors also provided direct technical advice to Iran, Sri Lanka, Bhutan and Indonesia COs for their programmes to support national and local capacity building for disaster risk management. In the case of Pakistan, the RCB support focused on practical advice on how to establish an effective and efficient aid coordination mechanism immediately after the devastating earthquake. Moreover, the Delhi-based Regional Disaster Reduction Advisor has been fully occupied with post-earthquake coordination and provision of early recovery support to UNDP Pakistan since October 2005. Strengthen regional and national mine action management and technical expertise In order to address the effects of threats posed by landmines and unexploded ordnance to human safety, and to contribute to peace, confidence building and recovery and development activities, the Regional Mine Action Advisor (MAA) supported COs and country team efforts in strengthening national mine action capacities including policy development, planning, management and training. The MAA completed a major four-month intervention to establish a new mine action management and capacity building project to support the Government of Afghanistan assume responsibility for the current UN (DPKO) managed mine action programme. Concurrently, direct technical advice was also provided to Lebanon and Iran on their National Mine Action Programmes, with particular emphasis on enhancing national capacity to manage, coordinate and monitor mine action legislation, policy, and strategic planning. In addition, support was provided in a range of areas; including resource mobilisation, programme development, implementation and M&E. Support was also provided to a range of stakeholders including: COs, Government Mine Action Programmes, NGOs and other enterprises, enabling the countries to carry out mine action planning including establishing operational goals to reduce and eliminate landmines and other Explosive Remnants of War (ERW), in compliance with UN policy, the Ottawa and CCW Conventions. In the third and fourth quarters of 2005, continued mine action support was provided to programme transition in Afghanistan, with support to the newly recruited UNDP Capacity Development Advisor based in Kabul. Advisory and technical support was also provided to the Thai Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Thailand Mine Action Centre. Both briefing and workshop support were provided to the global meeting of national Mine Action Directors and UN Advisors in Geneva on 19-24 September 2005. Direct support to the Mine Action Unit Team in New York middle management course conducted in Bangkok included presentations and administrative support to the 29 October post course workshop. Follow-up mission to Afghanistan was undertaken in mid December and concurrently commenced planning for a project reformulation mission to Iran for January 2006. 43 Capacity Development in the CPR Programme Area The work of the CPR area has been clearly oriented towards capacity development. In the tsunami emergency phase, the practice augmented technical capacity of COs and provided know-how in situation analysis, designing the flash appeal, and through the rosters of consultants. Medium-term focused activities addressed capacity needs of both sets of clients \u2013 COs and national counterparts.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{co