practice top prize at RBAP Knowledge Fair); \ufffd Sri Lanka \u2013 Atlas training, model and procedures resulting in six of eight sub- offices using Atlas with level of managers approving transactions; and, \ufffd Thailand \u2013 re-orientation of staff capacities to new programming modalities, partnership arrangements (including the private sector and NGOs) and complex implementation arrangement requirements. In order to strengthen management practice functions in other COs and Regional Centres based on demand, plans were elaborated during the April 2005 RR/DRR and Knowledge Fair Maldives\u2014Surge capacity to respond to crisis and recovery When the tsunami hit, UNDP/Maldives faced the challenge of responding to the catastrophe while possessing an existing capacity for an annual delivery of only USD 1.3 m as well as constraining ICT connectivity in the multi-island country. In response to the CO\u2019s request for support, RCB put together a SWAT team that, working with numerous other UNDP actors and other partners, including the pro-bono contribution from Deloitte and Touche, managed to rapidly produce needed operational capacity despite a limited local skills market. Results \u2013A credible well-managed programme has been built that now sustains a $20-$30M annual delivery. A hard won improvement in connectivity has also benefited UN organisations working in the Maldives. 47 for conducting integrated CO capacity building based on the \u201cToolkit for Managing Change and professionalisation\u201d in project management and other management sub-practices Outputs during the year included: (a) Improvement oriented CO Action Plans developed and were resource persons at Myanmar sub-regional learning event of ASEAN \u201clate-comers\u201d (Mekong Plus) group of five COs: Myanmar, Vietnam, Lao PDR, Cambodia and Mongolia. Later followed by a mission to Bhutan. (b) Learning launched for PRINCE2, and draft Results Management Guide self-study course leading to project management certification. Led by participants of the above six COs plus Thailand. A mission to Samoa and Fiji Multi-country offices took place in August 2005 with the participation of staff from the Solomon Islands sub-office and the Pacific Sub-Regional Centre (PSRC) Manager. Papua New Guinea was postponed to 2006 at RC/RR request.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3ddeffbd-d4d0-43ac-8259-2ac9aa86149e": {"__data__": {"id_": "3ddeffbd-d4d0-43ac-8259-2ac9aa86149e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "87545d552cb675ce9462b01cbabd75cbc545d5daf43718664f72084d9c540950"}, "2": {"node_id": "54953603-6d26-4d93-ace7-b2205e0e978a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e6b5423a5e582db95f0328271d3937de5d8fdf22cde0d4cd4612ddc4c4efbdff"}}, "hash": "31906d707ee1bf2cafd9339f0e1253e4d662ffeeecf2af931e32dea760e4134f", "text": "Papua New Guinea was postponed to 2006 at RC/RR request. The MPT 2005 Work plan Outputs addressed by this Pacific sub-region engagement