ublications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7ef861082ecf34a90c4648ed48d0ec5598fc07c2c7ee0d2a87059979bb944bb2"}, "3": {"node_id": "029db9c9-7c38-4a7d-8657-3031f81b64ed", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "75fa96173313f66fb6e5d57b1e27efbeda9d9fad50b74153ef5fcf5b869de4bb"}}, "hash": "dd860395ed2d40d050a39c54f9cf936bd86ae6ca32f8d0d3bf279acc02c1897a", "text": "Promote knowledge networks through a mix of ICTs for better access and sharing of tools, technologies, and information. 3. Support development of locally relevant content, awareness and advocacy initiatives, and promote knowledge management to facilitate greater e-services. Study best practices related to e-Governance initiatives and access to information policies when making ICT work for the poor The Asia Pacific Development Information Programme (APDIP) (www.adip.net) continues to deliver on its objectives through activities that involve awareness raising and advocacy, promoting ICT for development (ICT4D) policies and dialogue, building capacities, research, knowledge sharing and networking. APDIP relocated from its office in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia to the RCB in late April 2005. Apart from completing pre-determined and \u2018self-standing\u2019 programme activities developed for 2005, APDIP also actively initiated activities in collaboration with other practice areas from both RCB (Governance) and RCC (HIV/ AIDS and Gender). Dedicated practice area focal points were also appointed in APDIP to help the various practice teams in the RCB and RCC to further mainstream ICT4D components within their respective practice areas. Five key areas for APDIP have been on a) e-Government and e- Governance; b) ICT and Poverty Alleviation; c) Free and Open Source Software Alternatives for Development; d) Internet Governance; and e) Gender Dimensions of the Information Society. The following highlights some of the achievements of APDIP in 2005. The APDIP also continues to manage the one-stop shop and reference point of ICT4D Resources and key regional and national e-Government/ e-Governance related data, programmes, best practices and resources specific to the Asia-Pacific region. Policy Development and Dialogue APDIP aims to raise the awareness of ICT4D through promoting policy options; providing technical advisory services aimed at building capacities in the formulation and implementation of policies; and supporting efforts to share knowledge and lessons-learned through APDIP organised events, policy advice and publications. In total, an estimated 1,790 policy-makers and senior management from governments, CSOs, and national and media institutions participated in 25 events that the APDIP organised in 2005. Five thematic examples of major regional/ global events organised by APDIP in 2005 to engage senior policy-makers were: ICT For Development On the occasion of the World Summit on the Information Society (WSIS), held in Tunis, APDIP promoted UNDP\u2019s ICT4D initiatives in the Asia-Pacific region through the organization of and participation in a wide range of events and an exhibition at the UNDP \u201cSharing the Future \u201c Pavilion. In addition, APDIP organized and co-organized a number of parallel events, most notably related to Free/Open Source Software, Internet governance, and ICT for poverty alleviation. 51 Free and Open Source Software Alternatives for Development In partnership with the Cambodian Government the 2nd Free and Open Source Software (FOSS) consultation was held in Siem Reap, Cambodia where more than 111 Free and Open Source Software policy makers and practitioners from 20 Asia-Pacific countries participated in a regional consultation on the way forward to further enhance the documentation, advocacy, and capacity building initiatives on FOSS in the region. The event was inaugurated by the Deputy Prime Minister of Cambodia. Internet Governance Continuing its work on Internet governance, through the Open Regional Dialogue initiative, (ORDIG) APDIP provided substantial input to the UN Working Group on Internet Governance (WGIG). APDIP\u2019s input culminated in a paper submitted to WGIG for its deliberation and final report to the UN Secretary-General. The paper was the result and conclusion of a year-long process that included consultations in partnership with UNESCAP and others; a region-wide, multilingual survey, issue-based research, and online consultation. A number of notable outputs stemmed from the ORDIG initiatives, including a regional declaration \u2013 the Tehran Declaration, endorsed by governments from around the region; a multi-media training toolkit for policy- and decision-makers; country specific reports; research papers; and a primer aimed at raising awareness on the issues.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "029db9c9-7c38-4a7d-8657-3031f81b64ed": {"__data__": {"id_": "029db9c9-7c38-4a7d-8657-3031f81b64ed", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Na