://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "92bdd6bf519d92ed0a465326f7d6d12497e5be6e6edd5a5ce5bcc53e501a0f9f"}, "3": {"node_id": "435897fb-805a-4992-adde-dac2489198fa", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8e04a193bbdcfe70cecbe8f98123b6216102d6e416f5139d851a1b5c931a7223"}}, "hash": "9f0c043b3e74f3909595ffe713bc79fbc2c63e43d9633e42e1fe26949c2302ba", "text": "Asia-Pacific The region now has one of the fastest HIV infection rates in the world, with Asia having the second largest number of people living with HIV/AIDS, estimated at as many as 8 million. In spite of this, the sheer lack of visibility of HIV/ AIDS issues in the mainstream media remains a huge challenge. The ICT4D team (RCB) and the HIV/AIDS team (RCC) initiated a massive HIV/AIDS campaign with 6 partners (encompassing UN agencies, UNDP COs, INGO and private sector), and 12 participating national broadcast partners. The total investment is USD 1.7 million, with RCB's ICT4D programme's catalyst contribution at USD 40,000. National broadcasters from 12 countries were brought together to learn from previous HIV/AIDS-related productions, and to assist them to develop scripts of the most appropriate messages for their individual countries. Results \u201312 unique stories were aired on 1 December 2005 in conjunction with World Aids Day to an estimated 500 million viewers, with the broadcast also being distributed free in the region to national broadcasters and to CSOs for use in advocacy workshops. All partners have committed to promoting the content in major international and regional HIV/AIDS conferences in 2006. Requests have been received from Africa and Europe for the re-broadcast of the content. 52 information dissemination, capacity building initiatives. These include a pilot training of trainers\u2019 project; and a small grants programme in the Pacific Islands. Programmatic support for UNDP Country Offices in Asia-Pacific, UN Agencies; UNDP Global; Governments and Civil Society Organisations from other regions. APDIP provides advisory services for COs in programmatic ICT areas such as overall programme development and project document and proposal reviews. In addition, the team continues to serve as a general conduit for COs to link to resources and experts within the APDIP network.. The team manages the network of UNDP ICT Programme Officers/Focal Points in Asia-Pacific to address various programmatic issues relating to mainstreaming ICT for development, UNDP corporate framework on ICT for development, and topical ICT for development trends. APDIP also actively provided technical back-stopping and policy advice to UNDP COs; sister UN agencies; governments; and civil society organisations in other regions (Latin America and Africa). In addition, the team advised the UN systems on the development of new FOSS based website and back-end systems as well as provided consultations to the UN Joint Inspection Unit (JIU) on APDIP\u2019s Open Source projects, case studies and use for JIU to prepare the Unit\u2019s report on the Policies of United Nations System Organisations toward the Use of Open Source Software. Regional Linkages and Synergies APDIP has also partnered with UNESCAP, UNIFEM, UNICEF, ITU, UNAIDS, UNCRD and UNESCO in initiating, supporting and collaborating on regional ICT4D issues. APDIP continues to work with regional professionals and CSOs for research and content development activities, fielding missions and facilitating a variety of workshops and seminar activities. The team also partnered with several key regional CSOs to build their capacities to engage policy-makers on debating the larger issues of development with cross links to issues related to the MDGs and sustainable human development 53 Missions: Programme Development/Technical Backstopping/Policy Advice Services cited below include both missions and virtual technical backstopping. Country Practice / Service Line \u2013 Purpose Dates Specialist(s) 1. Sri Lanka Advice on Setup and Management of Mailing List and Interactive Portal for Tsunami Relief Coordination 1 January Khairil Yusof 2. Afghanistan Advice on ICT Portal for Afghanistan through UNDP/ICT Project 13 March Khairil Yusof 3. Samoa Advice on Development of FOSS Training and Certification of System Administrators and End Users Programme 14 April Khairil Yusof 4. India India Knowledge Management Partnership Project - Open Access/Open Content for Solution Exchange: An Initiative of the UN Country Team in India 14 April Sunil Abraham 5. Lao PDR Technical advice and Hosting Services for Protected Areas and Development in the Lower Mekong Region Project 19 May Khairil Yusof 6. Vietnam Presentation on \u201cICT and Globalisation\u201d for UNDP Vietnam 18 May James George 7. Bangladesh Advice on Strategic Programming \u2013 Situation Analysis, Examining Existing Projects/Initiatives, and Identifying Potential Areas of Focus and Specific Activities.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "435897fb-805a-4992-adde-dac2489198fa": {"__data__": {"i