 Special Unit for South-South Cooperation (SU-SSC) deemed it important to assist in strengthening the RCB\u2019s support to", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b248dd9c-47a4-4cc9-b733-17d5e01e4fe1": {"__data__": {"id_": "b248dd9c-47a4-4cc9-b733-17d5e01e4fe1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7db9d5fe9b5559fac13f4a263421d0fc09b91776d5417d9f3b2ebfdbbe6ebe60"}}, "hash": "7db9d5fe9b5559fac13f4a263421d0fc09b91776d5417d9f3b2ebfdbbe6ebe60", "text": "tsunami-affected countries by providing expertise from the South to the tsunami-affected countries in conceptualising and implementing immediate recovery projects. In Thailand, the advisory assistance of the SSC team led to the following projects being implemented in collaboration with Thai NGOs \u201cLivelihood Restoration of Fishery Communities in Affected Coastal Villages in Phang Nga Bay and Ranong Province (covering some parts of Phuket)\u201d; \u201cLivelihood and Ecology Restoration in Nine Tsunami-affected Sub-districts in Phang Nga Province\u201d; and, \u201cIndigenous Livelihood Restoration and Sustainable Ecology for Lanta Islands.\u201d In Indonesia, the South-South resources supported the recruitment of a Technical Advisor on Disaster Risk Management based in Aceh. Some of the significant results achieved include development of a regulatory mechanism for the Indonesian Bureau of Recovery and Reconstruction for quality of design for construction resistant to natural hazards; planning a centre of excellence at Syiah University for demonstration of the design of buildings that will withstand tsunami and earthquakes; assessment of building plans for government, UNDP and UN habitat as well as assessment of 10 proposals in \u201c Developing Community based Risk Reduction in Aceh and West Sumatra Provinces\u201d. The lack of international organizations and development agencies based in the Maldives prior to the tsunami meant that experienced staff in disaster risk management and recovery was virtually non-existent. The arrival of too many organisations at once made the situation worse. The South-South resources therefore supported national, regional and southern staff in the areas of shelter, helping affected families in 58 islands repair or reconstruct their houses. The resources were also used to support the rehabilitation of infrastructure, especially harbours destroyed by the tsunami. Lastly, South-South resources were provided for implementation support. The team assembled was responsible for procurement, financial management and How South-South Cooperation Complements Disaster Response and Risk Management Developing countries are unfortunately more vulnerable to disasters, yet often have important experience to share about how to reduce risk and how to cope. Local communities are first to suffer, but also the first to respond to disasters before any outside help arrives. South-South exchanges have leveraged existing knowledge and experiences to minimise vulnerability to hazards and better respond to crisis. In the aftermath of the Tsunami, the RCB tsunami response team identified critical positions to be supported in country offices, and 22 southern experts were deployed to Indonesia, Maldives, Sri Lanka and Thailand to help country offices programme resources and implement projects. The RCB engaged southern consultants to conduct training sessions for the private sector and government in Sri Lanka. Results \u2013 CO capacity was strengthened with targeted southern experts, and communities response and preparedness for natural disasters was enhanced. 57 other related services to ensure the UNDP office coped with sudden increase in resources from $1.5 million to $30 million for 2005. In the aftermath of the tsunami, UNDP and the other UN agencies took a lead role in housing construction, livelihood restoration, capacity building of community-based organisations and environmental issues. The demands of the recovery programme placed a burden on the UNDP country office. The South-South resources were used to fund a number of posts critical to the design and implementation of projects under the tsunami recovery programme. Some of the key achievements include UNDP taking a lead role in the establishment of the Government\u2019s Disaster Management Centre; organising of people\u2019s consultations on disaster management, with over 1100 meetings conducted; providing technical assessments on flash appeal projects; and preparing proposals for regeneration of damaged coastal ecosystems. In Sri Lanka, South- South resources were also used to train UN and Government representatives on alternative disaster damage assessment methods. Public and private sector representatives were trained in disaster risk management. In partnership with BRSP, South-South resources were used to provide Private sector partnership advisory services at the Regional Centre in Bangkok and the COs in Indonesia and Sri Lanka. The results of this work are documented under the Private sector Partnerships section. The SSC Unit works with other partners to advance the Hyogo Framework of Action (HFA) formulated by the World Conference for Disaster Reduction in January 2005. The Unit developed the preparatory assistance phase of a Global Facility that will address disaster risk management at community level. In this area, the team has: \u2022 Visited selected communities and consulted the local governments in the Philippines and China to study their pioneering approach in community based environmental monitoring and preparedness. A community awareness and preparedness workshop was held in the Philippines in which 52 representatives from eight regions shared lessons learnt; \u2022 Cooperated with the Philippines CO to identify specific projects that will enhance current initiative in the three municipalities of Quezon Province,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e98558d3-1f1f-4089-b520-c00055bf7706": {"__data__": {"id_": "e98558d3-1f1f-4089-b520-c00055bf7706", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Annual Report 2005", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "145835944df271fd23c0c11cdcc8923fec95f9161a6106ae69788471fd584c12"}, "3": {"node_id": "9dceb76b-4904-48df-af24-c478588e9a04", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/undp-regional-centre-bangkok-annual-report-2005", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Program