 adopt-an-island scheme. A documentary filmmaker, recommended by RCB, produced a Maldives film that ended up on BBC TV, the Lehrer News Hour. Adopt-an-Island live interviews were lined up with BBC World and CNBC. Features also ran in the Financial Times, the South China Morning Post and other media outlets. During the immediate aftermath of the 8 October 2005 earthquake, the Communications team identified international broadcasters and targeted print media to line up live international broadcast interviews with the UN Resident Coordinator and provided regular updated contact lists of reporters to UNDP Pakistan for their outreach in the country. At the end of the year, in the lead-up to the tsunami one-year anniversary, the Regional Communications Adviser provided on-the-ground support to UNDP Indonesia, generating news stories just prior to the commemoration which ran on major news wires. The RCB Communications team provided extensive promotional support to the Regional Aid Management team which resulted in coverage in the Economist, the Christian Science Monitor and other outlets. RCB Communications support to a UNDP Thailand television production on tsunami work with the sea gypsies was aired on the Lehrer News Hour and BBC. The Communications team also: \u2022 Organised and facilitated communications training: a three-day training workshop for 35 UNDP Communications staff from across the region; a two-day communications training workshop for 14 UNDP governance focal points from across the region; and a high-level communications training for 14 Resident Representatives and Deputy Resident Representatives organised in collaboration with COA NY; \u2022 Coached and provided feedback on 13 country offices\u2019 communications strategies. \u2022 A regional communications strategy was drafted; 62 \u2022 Provided editing and messaging support to the teams of the tsunami-affected countries, including support during the 17-day tsunami trip of the RBAP Regional Director and